#let lesson = (
title: [Unusual Attitudes and Emergencies]

,aim: [
Recognise and recover from nose-high and nose-low unusual attitudes, and manage in-flight emergency scenarios including fire, control difficulties, and partial system failures.
]

,overview: [
Lesson 4.5 covers E16, which expands on emergency content by adding UPRT fundamentals. This lesson also introduces a formal framework for aviation decision making (ADM). Aircraft control is always the first priority in unusual or novel situations, followed closely by _time_. How much time is available to solve the problem? The unusual attitude content connects directly to the spiral dive recovery from E9 and the stall awareness from E7 and E10. Emergency scenarios include in-flight fire, smoke or fumes, partial control failures, and instrument failures. The student operates as PIC throughout; the instructor introduces and demonstrates only the unusual attitude exercises, and poses the scenarios for the student to solve.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Describe the nose-high unusual attitude: causes, recognition (high pitch, low airspeed, high AoA), recovery sequence
- Describe the nose-low unusual attitude: causes, recognition (low pitch, high airspeed, high rate of descent), recovery sequence
- Explain why rolling wings level must precede backpressure in a nose-low recovery
- Explain various in-flight failure procedures including fire, smoke, instrument failure
- Explain why pilots might rush in their decision making and make a situation worse
- Apply an effective ADM (aviation decision making) to make more effective decisions

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Recover from a nose-high unusual attitude: push, full power if needed, roll wings level, establish controlled flight
- Recover from a nose-low unusual attitude: close throttle, roll wings level, ease out of the dive, establish controlled flight
- Identify and manage a simulated in-flight engine fire scenario from memory
- Identify and manage a simulated smoke/fumes scenario
- Manage the aircraft with a simulated partial control restriction
- Identify a failed instrument and adapt the LARI scan
- Use ADM to arrive at an effective solution to a novel problem

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [TEM] Identify the scenarios that lead to unusual attitudes: distraction, startle, spatial disorientation; brief mitigations before flight
- [HF] Proprioceptive and vestibular illusions: the body is not a reliable attitude reference; use the horizon; brief particularly for the nose-low scenario
- [HF] Aviation Decision Making: why it's important to have discipline in decision making, to not make the situation worse
- [CRM] Brief each emergency scenario before entering; both occupants confirm understanding of recovery
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Aerodynamics — spiral dive recognition and recovery *(Pg 106)*
- Aerodynamics — load factor, dynamic stall *(Pg 165, 173)*
- Aerodynamics — spin entry and recovery awareness *(Pg 170–171)*
- Human Factors — disorientation, vestibular and proprioceptive cues *(Pg 20)*
- Human Factors — undesired aircraft states, countermeasures *(Pg 44, 48, 51)*
- Human Factors — stress and fatigue *(Pg 36–40)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 35 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft model, whiteboard \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] Scenarios that produce unusual attitudes: distraction, task overload, inadvertent cloud, spatial disorientation
- [HF] Proprioceptive illusions: the body will tell the brain the aircraft is level when it is not; disorientation is genuine and rapid; always maintain visual flight conditions
- [HF] Aviation Decision Making: a strategy to make effective decisions, and avoid making situations worse

*Nose-High Unusual Attitude* (5 minutes)
- Recognition: high pitch attitude, airspeed reducing, AoA approaching critical, possible stall warning
- Recovery: push (reduce AoA), add power if attitude is moderate, roll wings level if bank is present
- If steeply nose-high with low airspeed: push forward first; reduce power if energy is excessive; roll to shortest path to horizon
- Connection to E7/E10: the nose-high unusual attitude is a precursor to the stall; recovery is a more urgent version of E7

*Nose-Low Unusual Attitude* (5 minutes)
- Recognition: low pitch attitude, airspeed increasing, high rate of descent, tight bank
- Recovery: close throttle, roll wings level with ailerons and rudder, ease back once wings are level — not before
- Connection to E9: this is the spiral dive recovery; the procedure is identical
- Do not apply backpressure before wings are level — this tightens the spiral and increases asymmetrical structural load

*In-Flight Fire* (5 minutes)
- Refer to POH for all procedures; cover the following procedures using the POH:
- Engine fire/smoke
- Cabin fire/smoke
- Electrical fire/smoke

*Aviation Decision Making* (10 minutes)
- What is the procedure for new/novel situations? How does the pilot ensure they are not making the situation worse?
- Time: after establishing aircraft control, _how much time?_ is the first question to ask and accurately answer; this stops panic, and starts problem solving mindset
- Assess all factors: take a moment to assess the situation and propose a plan
- Predict: try to imagine the scenario playing out; predict the problems you might encounter while performing plan; anticipate any resources you need and how to get them
- Evaluate: after implementing the plan assess the results - do they match your predictions?
- If aircraft control is questionable, assess aircraft handling in the landing configuration at a safe altitude before committing to the approach

*Partial Control and Instrument Failures* (5 minutes)
- Apply the ADM principle above to the following scenarios
- Trim failure: maintain control with primary controls; use power to reduce control forces where possible
- Partial control restriction: identify restricted axis; compensate with remaining controls; do not force; test the landing configuration with plenty of altitude for recovery
- Instrument failure: identify by cross-referencing other instruments; note failure; continue with remaining instruments; adapt LARI scan
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Student obtains NAIPS TAF/GAF; checks BOM radar; briefs conditions — smooth air required for unusual attitude training
- Student checks NOTAMs; briefs relevant items
- Student reviews maintenance release; briefs instructor
- Student briefs planned flight including HASSELL minimum height and each emergency scenario to be covered
- Participate in discussions with instructor about different scenarios, and how the ADM principles would apply

#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Receives brief
- Pose "what if" questions to the student during the briefing to see if they have understood the ADM concepts well. Each answer should start with establishing time available to solve the problem
- Assumes instructor role for unusual attitude and emergency content
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Observer/PIC Phase — Departure and Transit*]
Student operates as PIC. Instructor is silent observer. All ground operations, takeoff, departure, and transit conducted by student. HASSELL before UA exercise.

#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor Assumes Instructor Role — New Material*]

#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- Nose-high unusual attitude: instructor creates the attitude using a realistic entry (distraction or clipboard accidently placed on trim switch); demonstrates recovery
- Nose-low unusual attitude: instructor creates the attitude; patters recognition cues; demonstrates recovery — throttle, roll wings level, ease back
- In-flight fire scenario (simulated): instructor calls "engine fire"; patters immediate actions
- Smoke/fumes scenario: instructor calls "smoke in cockpit"; patters actions and ventilation
- Scenario task with student: Jammed flight controls; use the ADM procedure to walk through possible actions; run a control test; if the controls become jammed at 75 knots, can we add flaps 3?

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- Instructor returns to observer role.
- Unusual attitude practice: instructor creates attitude while student is heads-down on a task; student detects and applies correct recovery
  - Nose-high, wings level
  - Nose-high, with bank
  - Nose-low, wings level
  - Nose-low, with bank
- Fire simulation: instructor calls scenario; student executes from memory; patters each action
- Smoke/fumes simulation: student identifies and patters actions
- Trim failure simulation: instructor applies trim deflection without comment; student identifies, compensates, patters actions
- Participate in the jammed flight controls scenario with the instructor: offer suggested actions
- Scenario task: "You are at 3500 ft in the training area and there is smoke coming from behind the panel. Do we adopt best glide? What are your actions?"

#text(size:12pt)[*Observer/PIC Phase — Return*]
Student conducts return transit, circuit join, and landing independently.
]

,common_errors:[
- *Pulling back before wings level in nose-low recovery*: This is the most common and dangerous error — level wings first; reinforce the sequence every time.
- *Delay in fire action*: Fire immediate actions must be memory items — drill on the ground before flight.
- *Rushing decision making*: Immediately jumping to a suboptimal solution to an issue. _"How much time?"_
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Leads Debrief* (10 min): Student reviews each scenario; self-assesses recovery sequence and timing; identifies the cause for each unusual attitude that developed.
- *Instructor Supplements* (5 min): Adds observations
- *Theory Check* (5 min): Student states nose-low recovery sequence from memory; explains why backpressure must wait until wings are level.
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework. L4.6 is the Area Solo Suitability Assessment.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing (P) — may advance to L4.6*]
- *Nose-high recovery*: Pushes forward and levels wings; may apply light backpressure before fully level with manageable effect
- *Nose-low recovery*: Closes throttle; levels wings before significant backpressure; height loss manageable
- *Fire actions*: Executes from memory with minor sequencing error; recoverable
- *Decision making*: Acceptable actions with some prompting required. Decisions were reasonable and logical.

#text(size:12pt)[*Certificate Standard (C) — required before flight test*]
- *Nose-high recovery*: Correct sequence immediately; no stall; controlled
- *Nose-low recovery*: Throttle closed; wings levelled before backpressure; height loss ≤500 ft
- *Fire actions*: Memory items executed correctly and promptly in correct sequence without prompting
- *Smoke/fumes*: Identifies and manages without prompting; correct land decision
- *Trim/control failure*: Identifies and compensates correctly; makes correct continuation or landing decision
- *Decision making*: Always assesses time available before making decision, careful and correct thought process and uses available resources fully
- *Student-as-PIC*: All trained portions without any instructor input

- *Outcome*: Recorded in training record as P or C with specific comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Horizon clearly visible; ceiling >2500 ft AGL; smooth air essential; wind \<25 knots
- *Altitude*: All unusual attitude exercises above 2500 ft AGL; recoveries complete above 2000 ft AGL
- *Emergency Procedures*: All exercises clearly briefed; HASSELL before unusual attitude exercises; brief nose-high maximum angle and nose-low maximum airspeed before flight
- *TEM*:
  - Nose-high exercise: brief maximum nose-up attitude; instructor takes control if exceeded
  - Nose-low exercise: brief maximum airspeed before instructor intervenes; specify in knots
  - Fire simulation: do not actually close fuel selector in flight — brief the simulation distinction before departure
  - Monitor for spatial disorientation after prolonged unusual attitude recovery; allow reorientation before continuing
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aerodynamics: Pg 106, 165, 170–173 (spiral dive, load factor, spin entry and recovery)
  - Human Factors: Pg 20, 44, 48, 51 (disorientation, undesired aircraft states, countermeasures)
  - Human Factors: Pg 36–40 (stress, fatigue)
- Memorise the immediate actions for each emergency from this lesson before the area solo suitability assessment
- Prepare for L4.6 (Area Solo Suitability Assessment):
  - Review all Phase 4 elements: E9, E10, E14, E15, E16
  - Review all theory exam completion status: BAK, Air Legislation, Human Factors
- Reflect:
  - "What is the single most important action in recovering from any nose-low unusual attitude, and why must it happen before everything else?"
  - "What scan habit prevents unusual attitudes from developing? How does it connect to the LARI workcycle?"
]
)

